Prospera OS
Intent System Specification v1.2

File: system/intent/intent-system-v1.2.md
Status: Stable
Owner: Prospera Architecture Group
Category: System Specification
────────────────────────────────────────

Purpose

The Intent System provides the canonical, deterministic interpretation of every request made inside Prospera OS.
It defines what the system should do, ensuring that all downstream subsystems (Routing, Execution, Generation, Memory, Safety, etc.) operate on a validated and constitutionally-safe intent.

It guarantees:
• deterministic intent interpretation
• governance-approved intent classification
• safety-bound transitions
• SSOT lineage for every intent
• zero ambiguity in downstream routing

Version 1.2 integrates:
• Intent State Machine v2.0
• Predictive Safety Overlay v2.0
• Governance Validation Protocol v1.2

────────────────────────────────────────

Scope

Included:
• intent intake and normalization
• classification and validation
• deterministic interpretation
• intent state machine transitions
• predictive safety scoring
• intent lineage tracking

Excluded:
• user preference modeling
• probabilistic interpretation
• implicit emotional inference
• engine-level heuristics

────────────────────────────────────────

Intent Architecture (v1.2)

The Intent System consists of:

Intent Intake Gateway (IIG)
Receives raw intent input and normalizes structure.

Intent Normalization Engine (INE)
Enforces deterministic formatting and schema alignment.

Intent Classifier (IC)
Classifies the intent into predefined categories.

Intent State Machine v2.0 (ISM)
Handles deterministic transitions between intent states.

Predictive Overlay v2.0 (PO)
Provides safety risk estimation for intents.

Intent Lineage Recorder (ILR)
Maintains SSOT lineage for intent evolution.

────────────────────────────────────────

Intent Data Model

4.1 RawIntent
RawIntent {
  caller: subsystem,
  payload: object,
  context: object
}
4.2 IntentPayload
IntentPayload {
  intent_type: string,
  normalized_data: object,
  metadata: object
}
4.3 IntentState
IntentState {
  state: string,
  severity_level: number,
  lineage_hash: string,
  drift_markers: [string]
}
4.4 IntentResult
IntentResult {
  status: success | failure | escalated,
  new_state: IntentState,
  governance_notes: object
}
────────────────────────────────────────

5. Intent Flow (v1.2)
Stage 1 — Intake

• receive RawIntent
• validate structure and payload
• reject prohibited fields
• seal I1

Stage 2 — Normalization

• transform payload to canonical form
• apply deterministic schema
• seal I2

Stage 3 — Governance Validation

• enforce Kernel Constitutional Rules v1.2
• validate capability class
• ensure intent legality
• seal G1

Stage 4 — Classification

• classify intent into allowed categories
• assign severity levels
• compute constitutional risk markers
• seal C1

Stage 5 — Predictive Overlay v2.0

• compute anomaly risk
• detect drift patterns
• enforce predictive safety boundaries
• seal P1

Stage 6 — State Machine Transition

• apply Intent State Machine v2.0
• compute new deterministic state
• update lineage hash
• seal S1

Stage 7 — Output

• build IntentResult
• return new state
• commit lineage to SSOT

────────────────────────────────────────

6. Intent State Machine (ISM v2.0)

Allowed states:

• Raw
• Normalized
• Classified
• High-Intent
• Sensitive-Intent
• Restricted
• Escalated

State transitions must:

• follow deterministic rules
• satisfy governance constraints
• preserve identity boundaries
• prohibit implicit escalation

Forbidden transitions:

• Restricted → High-Intent
• Any → Privileged (unless Governance explicitly approves)
• Escalated → Normalized (requires Recovery System)

────────────────────────────────────────

7. Intent Boundary Rules

Subsystems must:

• supply valid RawIntent
• may not bypass normalization
• may not self-assign intent type

Engines may:

• consume IntentPayload
• never generate or modify intents

Modules may not:

• access or define intents directly

Prohibited:

• intent inference from personal data
• probabilistic interpretation
• modifying lineage hashes

────────────────────────────────────────

8. Drift Model (v1.2)

Type A — Minor Formatting Drift
• self-correctable during normalization

Type B — Classification Drift
• classification mismatch
• requires governance validation

Type C — Risk Escalation Drift
• predictive model anomaly
• escalate to Safety System

Type D — Constitutional Intent Drift
• illegal or impossible intent
• requires kernel arbitration

────────────────────────────────────────

9. Governance Integration

The Intent System v1.2 aligns with:

• Kernel Constitutional Rules v1.2
• Governance Validation Protocol v1.2
• Routing System v1.2
• Audience System v1.2
• Global Inter-System Contract v1.0

Intent must be:

• deterministic
• constitutionally valid
• lineage-consistent
• governance-auditable

────────────────────────────────────────

10. Versioning

v1.0 Initial Intent System
v1.1 Classification + governance integration
v1.2 State Machine v2.0 + predictive safety + constitutional alignment

